										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">What is a Python if else statement?&nbsp;</span></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">An if and else is a<a href="https://www.earthdatascience.org/courses/intro-to-earth-data-science/write-efficient-python-code/conditional-statements/" target="_blank" rel="noopener external" data-wpel-link="external"> conditional statement</a> that executes a block of code when certain conditions have been met.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><iframe loading="lazy" title="Python if else statements  – Python tutorial for beginners – CodeBerry Programming School" width="1080" height="608" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/cJbcCdhM8iI?feature=oembed" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>
<h3><span style="font-weight: 400;">Creating a Python if else statement</span></h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">To create a Python if else statement we begin by writing the word if and then we give it a condition and if that condition is true it moves on to the next line and runs that piece of code.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a href="https://codeberryschool.com/en/python-programming-course-for-beginners" target="_blank" rel="noopener external" data-wpel-link="external"><img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter wp-image-12196 size-full" src="https://codeberryschool.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Python-1-1.png" alt="Python if else statement" width="1024" height="340" srcset="/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Python-1-1.png 1024w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Python-1-1-300x100.png 300w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Python-1-1-768x255.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">So a basic if statement will have the word if followed by a condition and then a colon after which when we hit enter there will be an indentation. In this example, we will say that x = 20 and y =15 and then we will state the condition that says </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">if x is greater than y, print x.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">So what we&#8217;re saying here is that if the value for x is greater than the value for y, and these are both integers, it&#8217;s going to run the piece of code that prints out the number 20. As shown in the code below.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><iframe loading="lazy" src="https://trinket.io/embed/python/b2952f2f0a?start=result" width="100%" height="300" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"><span data-mce-type="bookmark" style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; overflow: hidden; line-height: 0;" class="mce_SELRES_start">﻿</span></iframe></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Suppose we change the value of y to 25 the code above will no longer run.&nbsp; This is because the condition above will no longer be met. However, if we change the condition to read if x was less than y we would then print x out again. As shown in the code below.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><iframe loading="lazy" src="https://trinket.io/embed/python/fb3f5180de?start=result" width="100%" height="300" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"><span data-mce-type="bookmark" style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; overflow: hidden; line-height: 0;" class="mce_SELRES_start">﻿</span></iframe></p>
<h3>Using the else condition in Python if else statement</h3>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">What if we want to do something else when the condition is not met. This is where the &#8220;</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">else&#8221;</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> comes in. If x is less than y, we are going to run a different piece of code. But if it is not met then we place another condition outside the indentation statement we are going to run this piece of code instead.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><iframe loading="lazy" src="https://trinket.io/embed/python/fbb5342656?start=result" width="100%" height="300" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"><span data-mce-type="bookmark" style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; overflow: hidden; line-height: 0;" class="mce_SELRES_start">﻿</span></iframe></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">As you can see in the code above the condition </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">x&gt;y</span><span style="font-weight: 400;"> is not met therefore the program opts to run the piece of code after the else statement which then prints out the string </span><span style="font-weight: 400;">“this is our else”</span><span style="font-weight: 400;">.It is important to note that it is all about true and false in if statements.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a href="https://codeberryschool.com/en/python-programming-course-for-beginners" target="_blank" rel="noopener external" data-wpel-link="external"><img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter wp-image-12028 size-full" src="https://codeberryschool.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Testimonial-2.png" alt="" width="1024" height="340" srcset="/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Testimonial-2.png 1024w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Testimonial-2-300x100.png 300w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Testimonial-2-768x255.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">We can also do the same with text or strings as well as shown in the example below.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><iframe loading="lazy" src="https://trinket.io/embed/python/6486f91fe4?start=result" width="100%" height="300" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"><span data-mce-type="bookmark" style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; overflow: hidden; line-height: 0;" class="mce_SELRES_start">﻿</span></iframe></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">If we change the name to ‘Fred’, then the statement is going to skip the first part and run the code after the else statement. As shown here.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><iframe loading="lazy" src="https://trinket.io/embed/python/0def0c59ff?start=result" width="100%" height="300" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"><span data-mce-type="bookmark" style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; overflow: hidden; line-height: 0;" class="mce_SELRES_start">﻿</span></iframe></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Another useful thing that we can do is we can use an if statement to check if something is present in a list. This is quite a common concept and quite handy to know.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">To begin this let&#8217;s create a list of names. Then write an if statement to check if any of the names are in the list or otherwise.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><iframe loading="lazy" src="https://trinket.io/embed/python/8173d39d03?start=result" width="100%" height="300" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"><span data-mce-type="bookmark" style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; overflow: hidden; line-height: 0;" class="mce_SELRES_start">﻿</span></iframe></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">If we change the condition and check if Jessica is on the list we are going to get a different output as illustrated by the code below.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><iframe loading="lazy" src="https://trinket.io/embed/python/fe49f6a60f?start=result" width="100%" height="300" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"><span data-mce-type="bookmark" style="display: inline-block; width: 0px; overflow: hidden; line-height: 0;" class="mce_SELRES_start">﻿</span></iframe></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400;">Always remember that you need the colon at the end and you need to indent the code after the colon and your else comes in the same line as your if.</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a href="https://codeberryschool.com/en/python-programming-course-for-beginners" target="_blank" rel="noopener external" data-wpel-link="external"><img loading="lazy" class="aligncenter wp-image-12197 size-full" src="https://codeberryschool.com/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Python-2.png" alt="" width="1024" height="340" srcset="/blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Python-2.png 1024w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Python-2-300x100.png 300w, /blog/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/Python-2-768x255.png 768w" sizes="(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px" /></a></p>
